EXIT ROW SEATING
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) regulations (14 CFR, Part 121 and 135) outline specific policies
and procedures U.S. air carriers must follow concerning exit row seating in aircraft.
The following content of the rules is being provided for your information and guidance.
SELECTION CRITERIA
No air carrier may seat a person in an exit row seat if it is likely that the person would be unable to perform
one or more of the applicable functions listed below because:
1. The person lacks sufficient mobility, strength, or dexterity in both arms and hands, and both legs to:
A. Reach upward, sideways, and downward to the location of emergency exit and exit slide operating mechanisms;
B. Grasp and push, pull, turn, or otherwise manipulate those mechanisms;
C. Push, shove, pull, or otherwise open emergency exits;
D. Lift out, hold, deposit on nearby seats, or maneuver over the seatbacks to the next row objects the size and weight of
over-wing window exit doors;
E. Remove obstructions similar in size and weight to over-wing exit doors;
F. Reach the emergency exit expeditiously;
G. Maintain balance while removing obstructions;
H. Exit expeditiously;
Stabilize an escape slide after deployment, or;
J. Assist others in getting off an escape slide;
2. The person is less than 15 years of age or lacks the capacity to perform one or more of the applicable functions without the
assistance of an adult comoanion. parent. or other re ative:
3. The person lacks the ability to read and understand instructions related to emergency evacuation provided by the air carrier in printed,
handwritten, or araphic form or the ability to understand oral crew commanas in te englisn language.
4. The person lacks sufficient visual capacity to perform one or more of the applicable functions shown on this card without the
